<POR_COPY_TXT><![CDATA[         Normal 0     false false false  EN-US X-NONE X-NONE                                                                                                                                                                               Normal 0     false false false  EN-US X-NONE X-NONE                                                                                                                                                                         Over forty scientists from six countries convened in Raleigh, NC on June 4-6 2012 to review the status and prospects of sea spray aerosol research.  Participants were researchers from the oceanography and atmospheric science communities, including academia, private industry, and government agencies. A workshop was held with the objectives of 1) identifying the most critical open questions regarding sea spray aerosol and developing a list of priorities for conducting novel research, and 2) ranking the most pressing science questions based on their feasibility impact on reducing the current uncertainty ranges for different processes. The recommendations from the working groups are summarized in a science prioritization matrix that is meant to prioritize the research agenda and identify areas of investigation by the magnitude of their impact on proposed science questions.  Strategies for laboratory studies, field measurements, remote sensing, and modeling research have been identified.  The workshop presentations are available online (http://www4.ncsu.edu/~nmeskhi/Marine_Aerosol_Workshop/WEBSITE.html). A manuscript outlining the discussions and recommendations of the breakout groups is in-press in Atmospheric Science Letters (ASL). In addition to NSF, support for the workshop was also provided by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE), National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) and Office of Naval Research (ONR).          Last Modified: 0